# Component size and layout

- One React component per file. Components that exceed ~250 lines must
  be decomposed into feature-folder siblings. Historical example:
  `ChatList.js` was 670 lines and now lives in `components/chat-list/`
  split into `ChatList`, `SearchBar`, `EmptyState`, `ProjectGroup`,
  `ChatCard`. Contemporary example: `AppContextMenu.js` was 268
  lines and now delegates its save/restore selection state to the
  `useSavedSelection` hook and its DOM helpers (`isEditableElement`,
  `findSelectionContainer`) to `utils/dom.js`. The initial decomposition
  landed the component near 180 lines of handlers + `<Menu>` JSX;
  subsequent feature adds (e.g. the link-open menu item that routes
  through the pywebview bridge in desktop mode and `window.open` in
  terminal mode) have grown it back toward the 250 soft limit while
  the decomposition continues to pay off — the extracted hook and
  DOM helpers stay consumed without duplication.
- `MermaidLightboxModal.js` is a canonical "decompose before growth"
  example: pan/zoom state and math live in `useSvgPanZoom` (with pure
  helpers in `utils/svgPanZoomModel.js`), toolbar actions render
  through `MermaidZoomControls`, and the defensive parse-error
  fallback panel lives in `MermaidLightboxFallback`. The modal
  component itself stays focused on `Dialog` layout and the
  interactive diagram-surface branch (viewport + transform layer),
  delegating both the toolbar trio and the source-fallback panel to
  its siblings. This split keeps the modal under the size limit while
  isolating "diagram surface", "zoom command bar", and "graceful
  source fallback" as three independent concerns.
- Duplicated UI across pages (dialogs, toolbars, cards) is extracted
  into `components/<shared-area>/`. The export format + warning
  dialogs lived twice in the codebase before the refactor and must
  never again.

# Shared logic and helpers

- Duplicated logic across pages (fetch + cancel effects, cookie
  read/write, event state machines, selection save/restore) lives in
  `src/hooks/`. Current examples: `useChatSummaries`, `useExportFlow`,
  `useExportWarningPreference`, `useSavedSelection`. Hooks have
  additional discipline of their own — see
  [frontend-hooks.mdc](frontend-hooks.mdc).
- Pure helpers (`formatDate`, `dbPathLabel`, cookie parsing, DOM
  inspection) live in `src/utils/`. A helper may not be copied into
  two components; promote it on sight.

```jsx
// Wrong: duplicated at the top of ChatCard and ChatMetaPanel
function formatDate(date) { /* ... */ }

// Right
import { formatDate } from '../../utils/formatDate';
```

# Theme ownership

- MUI theme tokens (`palette`, `sx`) own the visual language. CSS
  files in `src/` must **not** hard-code colors the theme already
  controls. Keep global CSS limited to font stacks, CSS-variable-
  driven scrollbars, and purely structural concerns. Motivating
  example: `frontend/src/index.css` previously hard-coded `#2D2D2D`
  for `pre` and `code` even in light mode.
- Contexts (`ColorContext`, `ThemeModeContext`) are defined in
  `src/contexts/`, one per file. Do not re-export contexts from
  `App.js`; import them from their defining file.

# Effects and export flow

- Use a cancellation flag
  (`let cancelled = false; ... return () => { cancelled = true; };`)
  for every `useEffect` that awaits a network request, and respect it
  after every `await` boundary.
- Reuse the `useExportFlow` hook for any new "export to file" UI
  rather than copying the format-dialog -> warning-dialog ->
  `exportChat()` state machine again.

# Memoize list-row components on hundreds-of-items lists

When a single page renders a list whose row count routinely reaches
hundreds (the chat-list grid is the motivating case — ~600 chats on
one developer's install), wrap the row component (and any
intermediate grouping component above it) in `React.memo` and make
**every** callback prop the parent feeds in `useCallback`-stable.
Without both halves of this discipline, any state change higher up
the tree (search input, expand toggle, theme switch) re-reconciles
the entire grid even when no row's data changed.

`ProjectGroup` and `ChatCard` (`frontend/src/components/chat-list/`)
are the canonical example. Two requirements together:

- Both export `memo(Component)` so React skips reconciliation when
  props are reference-equal.
- The owning page (`ChatList`) wraps `handleProjectToggle`,
  `handleCardExport`, `clearSearch`, and `handleSearchChange` in
  `useCallback` with accurate deps, and passes a single
  `(projectKey) => void` toggle handler instead of per-row arrow
  closures like `onToggle={() => toggleProjectExpand(project.key)}`.
  An inline closure recreates per render and silently busts the memo
  -- the symptom is "memoization looks applied but doesn't help",
  which is harder to diagnose than no memoization at all.

The companion lever for "list of hundreds" UIs is `<Collapse
mountOnEnter unmountOnExit>` on each grouping container. MUI's
`<Collapse>` keeps children mounted by default; with hundreds of
rows split across many collapsed groups, that means every list-data
swap still walks every row's subtree even though the user can only
see a fraction of them. The flags trade a one-time mount cost on
expand for skipping the reconcile entirely while collapsed; on the
chat-list grid that is a clear win because most groups are
collapsed at any given moment.

When in doubt: a list whose render time scales with the **total**
row count, not the **visible** row count, is the symptom this rule
is meant to prevent. Reach for memoization + stable callbacks
first; reach for a virtualization library only when the visible
window itself is too large for memoization to keep up.

# Third-party imperative-DOM libraries

When integrating a library whose primary output is imperative DOM mutation
(mermaid, prism, monaco, etc.), isolate it behind a dedicated React
component that owns the `useEffect` + cleanup, and a companion hook that
manages the library's global singleton (initialization, theme sync).
**Never** call the library's `.initialize` / `.render` / singleton-setup
function directly inside a React render function — only inside effects.

`MermaidBlock` + `useMermaid` are the canonical example:

- `useMermaid` (in `frontend/src/hooks/useMermaid.js`) owns
  `mermaid.initialize` — called in a `useEffect([darkMode])` once at the
  `MessageMarkdown` level so the singleton is always configured before any
  block renders.
- `MermaidBlock` (in `frontend/src/components/MermaidBlock.js`) owns the
  per-block async `mermaid.parse` + `mermaid.render` sequence (with the
  parse-first guard pinned in
  [`mermaid-rendering.mdc`](mermaid-rendering.mdc) under "Parse before
  render"), the diagram/source toggle state, the `latestRef` cancellation
  pattern (per [`frontend-hooks.mdc`](frontend-hooks.mdc)), and the error
  fallback UI. It also re-initializes mermaid immediately before each
  render pass because React runs child effects before parent effects, so
  the parent's `useMermaid` effect may not have run yet on the first
  mount.

A sibling component is allowed to **display** the SVG produced by the
owning component, but it must not call the library's imperative API
itself. The canonical example is
`frontend/src/components/MermaidLightboxModal.js`: it consumes the
`svg` already in `MermaidBlock`'s state via props and renders it
through `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`, but it never calls
`mermaid.render`, `mermaid.parse`, or `mermaid.initialize`. This keeps
the "library calls only inside effects of the owning component" rule
intact even when the same SVG is consumed by multiple presentation
surfaces, and it keeps the bomb-graphic risk closed by the parse-first
guard in [`mermaid-rendering.mdc`](mermaid-rendering.mdc) from being
re-opened by a duplicate render call. The same pattern applies to any
future modal / popover / off-screen surface for prism, monaco, or
similar imperative-DOM libraries.

When that sibling needs rich interaction (pan/zoom/select/inspect),
extract the interaction state machine into a dedicated hook under
`frontend/src/hooks/` instead of growing the presentation component
with pointer math and clamp logic. `useSvgPanZoom` is the mermaid
example of this pattern.
